		<div class="col-md-4" style="padding-left: 100px; padding-right: 20px; padding-bottom: 100px; padding-top: 100px;">
			<img src="img/TitleImage.jpeg" alt="Wearable Image" width="100%"/>
		</div>
		<h2 class="col-md-8" style="font-family: serif; text-align: center; color: floralwhite; font-size: 50px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0; padding-left: 20px; padding-right: 100px; padding-bottom: 100px; padding-top: 100px;">iFlight: System Design of an App for Flight Attendants</h2>
	</div>

	<div class=container>
		<div style="padding-top: 30px; padding-bottom: 30px;">As part of an Introduction to Contextual Design course I took, I worked on a project with four other undergraduate students to design a system that addresses the specific needs of flight attendants. Our guidelines were to select a specific user group to design a system for. Our final deliverable was in the form of an interactive high fidelity prototype we were able to click through and demonstrate to our peers. As we brainstormed a user group to focus on, we considered the circumstances – being in the midst of a global pandemic – and what industries might be affected by it. We decided to focus on the user needs of flight attendants.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Our research process consisted of the following components, which we did over the course of the semester:</div> 

		<li>Investigating Users: Conducting Interviews</li>
		<li>Research Synthesis: Creation of Work Models</li>
		<li>User Environment: Brainstorm and Design</li>
		<li>Prototypes: Wireframes, Paper and Low-Fidelity</li>
		<li>Evaluations: User Testing</li>
		<li>System Design: High Fidelity Prototype</li>

		<h3 style="padding-bottom: 30px; padding-top:50px">Investigating Users: Conducting Interviews</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">As a group, we conducted a total of five interviews with flight attendants. The flight attendants we interviewed consisted of current and retired employees for airlines based in Asia. Out of the five interviews, I conducted two in collaboration with another group member, where we rotated between notetaker and facilitator roles.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Speaking with flight attendants gave us more insight into their daily tasks. Distributed across first class, business class and economy class based on experience level, flight attendants are responsible for checking equipment on the aircraft, conducting meal checks with airline caterers, helping passengers to their seats, conducting safety checks, servicing food and beverages, meeting passenger requests throughout the flight, preparing for landing, and facilitating a cleanse of the aircraft and final safety checks. Their main goal is to ensure passengers travel comfortably and safely.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom:  30px;">The main problems the flight attendants we interviewed face can be summarized in the following three categories:</div>

		<ol>
		<li><b>Safety and Security</b>: Many “what ifs” can happen if safety procedures are not carried out properly</li>
		<li><b>Time Management</b>: Flight attendants have many tasks to juggle prior and during the flight – it is easy to forget certain steps.</li>
		<li><b>Difficulty with Customer Service</b>: Hospitality and customer service is a significant part of the role – sometimes there are difficult passengers on the flight who flight attendants have to deal with.</li>
		</ol>

		<div style="padding-top:  20px; padding-bottom: 30px">These problems shed light on various opportunities:</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">A common thread between these three categories is the importance of communication to ensure safety and security checks run smoothly, tasks are delegated evenly to address issues of time management, and customer needs are met. We also identified breakdowns in communication between stakeholders. For instance, while supervisors use iPads to manage information, some of the flight attendants we spoke to rely on physical post-it notes to communicate responsibilities within the galley. <b>Facilitating better communication may help avoid unnecessary back and forth trips between the cabin and the galley and prevent important information from getting lost or misunderstood.</b></div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 50px;">We also identified addressing the emotional labor flight attendants experience as an opportunity to iterate on. Throughout the interviews, we found that flight attendants experience difficulty dealing with drunk, argumentative or demanding customers with unrealistic requests, which may require them to manage their emotions to do their job. <b>Focusing on mental health and addressing the emotional labor flight attendants experience was a potential area to build on.</b></div>

		<h3 style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Research Synthesis: Work Models</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">To synthesize our interview findings, we created several work models, including an <b>affinity diagram, sequence diagram, flow model and cultural model.</b> I worked with two other team members on the affinity diagram and sequence diagram.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">The affinity diagram, featured below, summarizes the tasks that our users perform. We separated these tasks into four main categories: safety and security, customer service, organization and time management, and teamwork.</div>

		<img src="img/AffinityDiagram.jpeg" alt="Affinity Diagram" width="100%" style="padding-bottom: 30px;"/>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">The sequence diagram, featured below, represents the multitude of tasks flight attendants have to do and the breakdowns they experience at each phase (represented by the lightning bolts in the diagram).</div>

		<img src="img/SequenceDiagram.jpeg" alt="Sequence Diagram" width="100%" style="padding-bottom: 30px;"/>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 50px;">Creating these work models helped us identify common breakdowns our target users were facing. It was not only easier to see patterns in a visual manner but also made it easier to present our findings to others. After meeting as a group to discuss our findings from creating these work models, we decided to focus on the need for <b>enhanced communication between flight attendants to address their time management and customer service breakdowns.</b></div>
		
		<h3 style="padding-bottom: 30px;">User Environment: Brainstorm and Design</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">We conducted a brainstorming session over a call, where we each communicated the concerns our users expressed and where common breakdowns occur. After discussing our focus area, we brainstormed various ideas of system designs to proceed with.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">For our design concept, we decided on a wearable device to be worn on the wrist of our users. This wearable would help our users manage their tasks and communicate in an efficient and organized manner with their colleagues. We decided on a wearable device as the cabin crew may not have the capacity to constantly check their phones throughout the flight. Furthermore, a wearable would be subtle and can act as an accessory that matches their uniforms.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">This wearable device would provide flight attendants with the following:</div>

		<li>Easy access to in-flight information</li>
		<li>Transparency across the cabin crew</li>
		<li>Efficient communication between cabin crew members</li>
		<li>Ability to assign, monitor and communicate tasks across the aircraft</li>

		<div style="padding-top: 30px; padding-bottom: 30px;">An important part of the process is to note limitations and constraints. We identified a couple that we might encounter if we were to implement our design:</div>

		<li>Restricted use of signal when the aircraft is in the air</li>
		<li>Security issues pertaining to sharing sensitive information across devices</li>
		<li>Cost increases to produce and maintain the device</li>
		<li>Small screen size poses challenges in some of the features we hope to implement, including a chat functionality that would involve typing</li>

		<h3 style="padding-top:  50px; padding-bottom: 30px;">Prototypes: Wireframes, Paper and Low-Fidelity</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom:30px;">After discussing focus areas to address in our designs, we worked on creating prototypes of the user interface, featured in the images below. I was responsible for creating the paper prototype, which was an interesting method as it allowed me to easily move physical copies of screens around to see if different orders flowed better.</div>

		<div class="row">
