		<h3 style="padding-top:  50px; padding-bottom: 30px;">Evaluations: User Testing</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">To test our designs, we conducted three evaluations. Two of the evaluations were conducted with our target users (current and former flight attendants) and one was conducted with people who have no prior knowledge of the airline industry, which was still informative to test usability. For all evaluations, we used the Think Aloud method, where we asked evaluators to talk through each decision they made, and the Wizard of Oz technique, which allowed users to interact with the interface prior to its implementation. 

		For our evaluations, we provided users with specific tasks to complete and asked them to share their understandings and concerns out loud with us. The list of tasks are included below: </div>

		<li>Unlock the off-duty screen</li>
		<li>Check your messages</li>
		<li>Identify new messages</li>
		<li>Enter a chat room</li>
		<li>Send a message</li>
		<li>Adjust settings (brightness and text size)</li>
		<li>Switch to night mode</li>
		<li>Check calendar and add a new event</li>
		<li>Synch to the flight you are currently on</li>
		<li>Accept passenger service requests</li>
		<li>Check tasks</li>
		<li>Reassign tasks to other flight attendants</li>
		<li>Switch status to "Do Not Disturb"</li>
		<li>Check for flight information</li>
		<li>Check for passenger food and beverage information</li>
		<li>Perform safety check for landing</li>

		<div style="padding-top: 30px; padding-bottom: 30px;">Based on our user evaluations, here's what worked:</div>

		<li>Users were able to easily find the settings menu and home screen; they found non-flight attendant specific workflows easy to follow</li>
		<li>Spoke highly of the wearable smartwatch form</li>
		<li>Appreciated the use of familiar icon symbols, as it allowed for smooth navigation</li>
		<li>Flight attendant evaluators liked the meal restriction summary page and noted the system design demonstrates an understanding of cabin crew needs and breakdowns</li>

		<div style="padding-top: 30px; padding-bottom: 30px;">Evaluators also expressed concerns and difficulties. Here's what didn't work:</div>

		<li>Difficulty viewing certain text and images on the screen due to the size of the interface</li>

		<li>Worried about missing notifications on the lock screen</li>

		<li>Navigation can be refined to be more clear</li>

		<li>Confusion about the audio to text functionality – worried about the possibility of errors as the aircraft can be noisy and might pick up other sounds</li>

		<li>Unsure about the difference between the on-duty and off-duty lock screens</li>

		<li>Concerned about poor connectivity in the air</li>

		<h3 style="padding-top:  50px; padding-bottom: 30px;">System Design: High-Fidelity Prototype</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">We iterated on our prototypes based on the feedback we received from the evaluations and user tests. As a group, we discussed the overall concept, features we wanted to add and changes that needed to be made. Three of our group members were responsible for building the final high-fidelity prototype in Figma, and I was responsible for writing up and communicating important features of our final design and future avenues we could take if we had more time, which I did in collaboration with another group member.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">The final design is a wearable device that improves workflows and minimizes stress for flight attendants by allowing them to keep track of their tasks, communicate and delegate tasks to one another, manage their schedules and access important flight information. Some of the key screens and features are summarized as follows:</div>

		<li><b>Chat Function</b>: assists users with communication through audio to text functionality, a keyboard, a pen functionality, and pre-loaded frequently used phrases.</li>
		<li><b>Calendar Function</b>: allows users to view their own schedules, which they can organize through the “Events Details” screen. They also have access to a roster to determine which colleagues are on their flight.</li>
		<li><b>Sync Flight Function</b>: allows users to select and connect with their flights through Bluetooth.</li>
		<li><b>On-Duty Lock Screen</b>: allows users to change their availability status. They can also accept passenger requests and view the tasks that they were delegated.</li>
		<li><b>On-Duty Home Screen</b>: users can view their tasks through a drop down menu, which addresses the problem of notifications disappearing prior to the completion of a task.</li>
		<li><b>Flight Information Screen</b>: provides information about flight departure and arrival times, weather, gate number, etc.</li>
		<li><b>Dining Information Screen</b>: informs users of passenger dietary restrictions through a color-coded visual seating chart of the aircraft.</li>
		<li><b>To-Do Checklist</b>: allows users to check off tasks when they complete them.</li>
		<li><b>Aircraft Section Preview Screen</b>: allows users to identify passengers who have requested service and where they are seated.</li>

		<div style = "padding-top: 30px; padding-bottom: 30px;">Below are annotated images of our high-fidelity prototype and a link to a video walk-through of our final design:</div>

		<a href="https://youtu.be/WNS2BMe8_dM" style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Video Demonstration</a>

