		<h3 style="padding-top:  50px; padding-bottom: 30px;">Conclusion + Recap</h3>


		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Engaging in the contextual design process, we started by selecting a target user group, determining their specific needs and goals, and ended with a high-fidelity prototype of our system design. The user group we decided to focus on were flight attendants, which we found interesting given that their role requires them to do many important tasks such as safety checks, but is also largely customer-facing, which may require additional emotional management. On top of that, their industry was largely impacted by the pandemic, so we were interested in hearing about their experiences.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 50px;">We started by understanding user needs by conducting semi-structured interviews, which means we had a list of prepared questions but pivoted depending on the direction of the discussion. Using the qualitative interview data, we constructed work models to organize and represent our findings in a visual manner. Afterwards, we met as a group to brainstorm and design our user environment. Based on our discussions as a group, we each worked on various low-fidelity prototypes to determine what the user interface would look like, which we used to conduct our user tests. Based on the evaluations from our user tests, we designed a high-fidelity prototype of a wearable system that assists flight attendants in time management and communication to enhance their workflow and address the user needs they expressed.</div>

		<h3 style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Future Work</h3>


		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Future work could focus on handling errors within the chat functionality. We tried to combat this by providing the user with multiple options beyond a keyboard, such as audio to text, a dictionary of key phrases and a pen function, but sometimes less is more. More options does not necessarily make it easier to use the chat function and minimize errors made when using this screen – future work could iterate on this.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">If we had more time, we could have also conducted more evaluations and user tests to ensure optimal usability of our device. In this next round, we would use our high-fidelity prototype to conduct user tests. While we were able to address many user needs and implement many features, I believe we can still simplify our design to make it more user friendly.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Considering the size of the device is small (as it is a wearable watch), it might be worth redesigning the screens that contain seating information (such as the Dining Information and Aircraft Section Preview Screens), as it looks cramped and can be difficult to view on such a tiny device.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 50px;">Finally, another issue we wanted to address but did not get the chance to are the mental health and emotional labor issues our target users expressed, especially during the pandemic and its effects on the travel industry. Future iterations could address mental health and wellness.</div>

		<h3 style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Reflections + Takeaways</h3>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">Working on this project over the course of the semester taught me a lot about the design process. As this was my first time learning about contextual design, having the opportunity to work on a semester-long project and experience the process first hand was the best way to learn.</div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 30px;">One of my biggest takeaways is that our <b>users are the number one priority.</b> We cannot simply assume what our users need, but rather we need to gain an understanding of their specific needs and goals by conducting interviews and user tests. My sociology background came in handy when we were writing interview questions, as I was able to craft questions that allowed us to better understand user needs without directly asking what they need. Allowing interviewees to talk about their tasks and processes allowed them to identify new breakdowns or issues they may not have come in with. <b>Being open to opportunities for growth you may not have come in with was a big takeaway for me.</b></div>

		<div style="padding-bottom: 50px;">Finally, <b>strong teamwork and collaboration proved to be a driving force</b> throughout this project. We were able to delegate tasks that played to our unique strengths, while also providing each of us with  opportunities to learn and grow.</div>

